DataElement.preferredName: Gynecologic Fallopian Tube Tumor Federation of Gynecology and Obstetrics (FIGO) 2009 Stage
DataElement.preferredDefinition: Anatomic extent of the primary fallopian tube carcinoma based on surgical pathologic examination.

DataElementConcept.preferredDefinition: Of or relating to or practicing gynecology; pertaining to the health issues of women._A benign or malignant tissue growth resulting from uncontrolled cell proliferation. Benign neoplastic cells resemble normal cells without exhibiting significant cytologic atypia, while malignant cells exhibit overt signs such as dysplastic features, atypical mitotic figures, necrosis, nuclear pleomorphism, and anaplasia. Representative examples of benign neoplasms include papillomas, cystadenomas, and lipomas; malignant neoplasms include carcinomas, sarcomas, lymphomas, and leukemias._One of a pair of tubes that extend from the uterus to each of the ovaries. Following ovulation the egg travels down the fallopian tube to the uterus where fertilization may or may not occur._The extent of a cancer within the body, especially whether the disease has spread from the original site to other parts of the body.

ObjectClass.preferredDefinition: Of or relating to or practicing gynecology; pertaining to the health issues of women.:(NEE-o-PLAY-zha) Abnormal and uncontrolled cell growth.

Concepts.longName: Neoplasm
Concepts.definition: A benign or malignant tissue growth resulting from uncontrolled cell proliferation. Benign neoplastic cells resemble normal cells without exhibiting significant cytologic atypia, while malignant cells exhibit overt signs such as dysplastic features, atypical mitotic figures, necrosis, nuclear pleomorphism, and anaplasia. Representative examples of benign neoplasms include papillomas, cystadenomas, and lipomas; malignant neoplasms include carcinomas, sarcomas, lymphomas, and leukemias.

Concepts.longName: Fallopian Tube
Concepts.definition: One of a pair of tubes that extend from the uterus to each of the ovaries. Following ovulation the egg travels down the fallopian tube to the uterus where fertilization may or may not occur.

ValueDomain.preferredName: Fallopian Tube Carcinoma Federation of Gynecology and Obstetrics (FIGO) 2009 Stage
ValueDomain.preferredDefinition: A carcinoma arising from the fallopian tube which is attached to the uterine corpus (uterine body). Most patients are postmenopausal, and postmenopausal bleeding is the most frequently seen symptom. Morphologically, the majority of fallopian tube carcinomas are serous or endometrioid adenocarcinomas._An international organization with a mission to promote the wellbeing of women and to raise the standards of practice in obstetrics and gynecology. They are the creator of staging criteria to describe the extent and spread of gynecologic malignancies._A number with no fractional part, including the negative and positive numbers as well as zero.::2009_The extent of a cancer within the body, especially whether the disease has spread from the original site to other parts of the body.

Concepts.longName: Fallopian Tube Carcinoma
